Class & Object — Interview Q&A (Easy → Hard)
Aligned with your class.py and Object.py notes: class vs object, __init__, self, attributes/methods, class vs instance vars, encapsulation, __str__/__repr__, copying, identity, and common traps.
________________________________________
Level 1: Easy
Q1. What is a class in Python?
A: A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines attributes (data) and methods (behavior).
class Person:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
________________________________________
Q2. What is an object in Python?
A: An object is an instance of a class — a real usable entity created from the blueprint.
p = Person("Alice", 20)   # p is an object
p.say_hello()
________________________________________
Q3. What is the difference between a class and an object?
A:
Class	Object
Blueprint / template	Real instance
Defined once	Can create many from one class
Person	p1 = Person(...), p2 = Person(...)
class Fruit:
    pass
apple = Fruit()   # Fruit = class, apple = object
________________________________________
Q4. How do you create a class and an object?
A:
class Car:
    def __init__(self, brand, year):
        self.brand = brand
        self.year = year
my_car = Car("Toyota", 2020)   # object creation
print(my_car.brand)            # Toyota
________________________________________
Q5. What is __init__? Is it a constructor?
A: __init__ is the initializer. It runs after the object is created to set initial attributes. In Python it is commonly called a constructor, but the true object creation happens via __new__.
class Student:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
s = Student("Alice")
________________________________________
Q6. What is self?
A: self is a reference to the current object instance. It is the first parameter of instance methods and is passed automatically when you call obj.method().
class Person:
    def say_hello(self):
        print(f"Hello, my name is {self.name}")
self is a convention, not a keyword — but always use self.
________________________________________
Q7. What are attributes and methods?
A:
•	Attributes — data stored in an object (name, age)
•	Methods — functions defined inside a class that operate on the object
class Car:
    def __init__(self, brand):
        self.brand = brand      # attribute
    def honk(self):             # method
        print(f"{self.brand} says Honk!")
________________________________________
Q8. How do you access attributes and call methods?
A:
car1 = Car("Toyota")
print(car1.brand)   # access attribute
car1.honk()         # call method
________________________________________
Q9. Can you create multiple objects from the same class?
A: Yes — each object has its own data:
class Point:
    def __init__(self, x, y):
        self.x = x
        self.y = y
p1 = Point(1, 2)
p2 = Point(4, 5)
print(p1.x, p1.y)   # 1 2
print(p2.x, p2.y)   # 4 5
________________________________________
Q10. What happens if you forget parentheses when creating an object?
A: You get the class itself, not an instance:
obj = Person          # class reference, not object
obj2 = Person("Raj", 28)   # actual object
print(type(obj))      # <class 'type'> related / class object
print(obj2.name)      # Raj
________________________________________
Q11. What error occurs if you miss a required __init__ argument?
A: TypeError:
# p = Person("Bob")   # TypeError: __init__() missing 1 required positional argument: 'age'
________________________________________
Q12. What error occurs if you forget self in a method?
A: TypeError: takes 0 positional arguments but 1 was given — Python still passes the instance.
class Cat:
    def speak():      # missing self
        print("Meow")
# c = Cat(); c.speak()  # TypeError
________________________________________
Q13. What is isinstance()?
A: Checks if an object is an instance of a class (or subclass):
class Animal:
    pass
dog = Animal()
print(isinstance(dog, Animal))   # True
________________________________________
Q14. What is the difference between type(obj) and id(obj)?
A:
•	type(obj) — returns the class/type of the object
•	id(obj) — unique identity (memory address) of the object
print(type(dog))   # <class '__main__.Animal'>
print(id(dog))     # e.g. 140712345
________________________________________
Q15. What is encapsulation at a basic level?
A: Hiding internal data and exposing it only through methods:
class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, balance=0):
        self.__balance = balance   # "private"
    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance
________________________________________
Level 2: Medium
Q16. What is the difference between class variables and instance variables?
A:
•	Class variable — shared by all objects
•	Instance variable — unique to each object
class Student:
    school = "ABC High School"   # class variable
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name         # instance variable
s1 = Student("Sai")
s2 = Student("Shrihansh")
print(s1.school, s2.school)   # both ABC High School
________________________________________
Q17. What is variable shadowing with class vs instance attributes?
A: Assigning via an instance creates an instance attribute that shadows the class attribute:
s1.school = "New School"
print(s1.school)          # New School (instance)
print(s2.school)          # ABC High School (class)
print(Student.school)     # ABC High School
________________________________________
Q18. What are instance methods, class methods, and static methods?
A:
Type	Decorator	First arg	Use
Instance	none	self	Works with object data
Class	@classmethod	cls	Works with class data
Static	@staticmethod	none	Utility; no self/cls
class MathOps:
    base = 10
    @classmethod
    def get_base(cls):
        return cls.base
    @staticmethod
    def add(x, base):
        return x + base
________________________________________
Q19. What is __str__ vs __repr__?
A:
•	__str__ — user-friendly string (print(obj), str(obj))
•	__repr__ — unambiguous / debug representation (repr(obj))
class Book:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title
    def __str__(self):
        return f"Book: {self.title}"
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Book('{self.title}')"
________________________________________
Q20. How do you add/get/delete attributes dynamically?
A:
class Empty:
    pass
obj = Empty()
obj.x = 10                    # add
setattr(obj, 'y', 20)         # add/modify
print(getattr(obj, 'y'))      # 20
print(hasattr(obj, 'x'))      # True
delattr(obj, 'x')             # delete
________________________________________
Q21. What does == vs is mean for objects?
A:
•	== — value equality (uses __eq__ if defined)
•	is — identity (same object in memory)
user1 = User("alice")
user2 = User("alice")
print(user1 == user2)                 # False (default: different objects)
print(user1.username == user2.username)  # True
print(user1 is user2)                 # False
________________________________________
Q22. What happens when you assign one object to another variable?
A: Both names point to the same object (aliasing):
a = [10]
b = a
b.append(20)
print(a)   # [10, 20]
Same for custom objects — no copy unless you explicitly copy.
________________________________________
Q23. What is shallow copy vs deep copy for objects?
A:
import copy
class Data:
    def __init__(self, numbers):
        self.numbers = numbers
data1 = Data([1, 2, 3])
data2 = copy.copy(data1)       # shallow
data3 = copy.deepcopy(data1)   # deep
data1.numbers[0] = 99
print(data2.numbers)   # [99, 2, 3] — shared list
print(data3.numbers)   # [1, 2, 3]  — independent
________________________________________
Q24. What are private attributes (__)? Are they truly private?
A: Name mangling: __balance becomes _ClassName__balance. Not true privacy — a convention + mangling, not a security lock.
class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, owner, balance):
        self.owner = owner
        self.__balance = balance
    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance
acc = BankAccount("Bob", 1000)
# print(acc.__balance)              # AttributeError
print(acc.get_balance())           # 1000
print(acc._BankAccount__balance)   # 1000 — still accessible
________________________________________
Q25. Can objects be passed to and returned from functions?
A: Yes:
class Rectangle:
    def __init__(self, width, height):
        self.width = width
        self.height = height
def area(rect):
    return rect.width * rect.height
print(area(Rectangle(6, 7)))   # 42
________________________________________
Q26. What is operator overloading with objects?
A: Define special methods so operators work on your objects:
class Vector:
    def __init__(self, x, y):
        self.x, self.y = x, y
    def __add__(self, other):
        return Vector(self.x + other.x, self.y + other.y)
    def __str__(self):
        return f"<{self.x}, {self.y}>"
print(Vector(1, 2) + Vector(3, 4))   # <4, 6>
________________________________________
Q27. What is the difference between deleting an instance attribute and a class attribute?
A:
s1.school = "New School"
del s1.school
print(s1.school)   # falls back to class variable "ABC High School"
Deleting an instance attribute restores lookup to the class attribute if it exists.
