Q28. What happens if you call an instance method on the class without an instance?
A: Usually TypeError — self is missing:
# Student.display()      # TypeError
Student.display(s1)      # OK if you pass instance manually
________________________________________
Q29. Can you use custom objects as dictionary keys?
A: Only if they are hashable (implement __hash__ and __eq__ properly). Default mutable custom objects are usually not safe as keys unless made hashable by design.
# Built-in immutables work as keys; custom objects need careful __hash__/__eq__
________________________________________
Q30. What is the difference between Person() and Person?
A:
Person      # the class object
Person()    # creates a new instance (calls __init__)
________________________________________
Q31. How do you check if an object has an attribute before using it?
A:
if hasattr(p, "age"):
    print(p.age)
print(getattr(p, "email", "N/A"))   # safe with default
________________________________________
Q32. What is method overriding (basic OOP with class/object)?
A: Child class redefines a parent method; calling it on a child object uses the child’s version:
class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        print("Animal speaks.")
class Dog(Animal):
    def speak(self):
        print("Woof!")
Dog().speak()   # Woof!
________________________________________
Q33. What is an abstract class briefly, and how does it relate to objects?
A: An abstract class cannot be instantiated directly; subclasses must implement abstract methods:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Shape(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self):
        pass
# Shape()  # TypeError
Circle(5).area()  # OK if Circle implements area
________________________________________
Q34. Real-world example of classes and objects together?
A: Library system — Book and Library classes; each book is an object with state (is_lent) and behavior (lend, return_book):
book1 = Book("The Alchemist", "Paulo Coelho")
lib = Library()
lib.add_book(book1)
lib.lend_book("The Alchemist")
