Q49. Can __init__ return a value?
A: No. __init__ must return None. Returning anything else raises TypeError.
# def __init__(self): return 5  # TypeError
To customize creation, override __new__.
________________________________________
Q50. What is composition vs inheritance (class/object design)?
A:
•	Inheritance — “is-a” (Dog is an Animal)
•	Composition — “has-a” (Library has Book objects)
class Library:
    def __init__(self):
        self.books = []   # composition: Library has Books
Prefer composition when you need flexibility over deep inheritance trees.
________________________________________
Q51. What is the output?
class A:
    def __init__(self):
        self.value = 10
a = A()
b = A()
print(a is b)
print(a.value is b.value)  # small ints may be interned
A:
False
True (often, due to int interning for small ints)
Objects are different; immutable values may share identity due to Python optimizations. Don’t rely on is for values.
________________________________________
Q52. How do __str__ and default object printing relate?
A: Without __str__/__repr__, print(obj) shows something like <__main__.Book object at 0x...>. Defining __str__ makes printed output readable for users.
________________________________________
Q53. What is monkey patching an object/class?
A: Dynamically adding/changing attributes or methods at runtime:
def new_honk(self):
    print("Beep!")
Car.honk = new_honk
car1.honk()
Powerful but can make code harder to maintain.
________________________________________
Q54. Design question: BankAccount — why use class + object instead of plain variables?
A: Because you need:
•	Multiple accounts with separate state
•	Encapsulated rules (deposit, withdraw)
•	Clear identity per account object
•	Reusable blueprint (BankAccount class)
acc1 = BankAccount("Bob", 1000)
acc2 = BankAccount("Amy", 500)
acc1.deposit(200)
